WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.073 --> 00:00:01.860
- I really do not like being the guest.

00:00:01.860 --> 00:00:03.150
It's my dream to be the guest,

00:00:03.150 --> 00:00:06.210
I think being the guest
is easier in some way,

00:00:06.210 --> 00:00:07.560
but I don't like it.

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:09.750
- So should Nick and I be asking
you how you make decisions?

00:00:09.750 --> 00:00:11.340
- I have no framework
for making decisions.

00:00:11.340 --> 00:00:13.620
It's all chaos and panic every single day.

00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:15.150
- You said that you think some portion

00:00:15.150 --> 00:00:16.650
of the "Decoder" audience just wants you

00:00:16.650 --> 00:00:19.334
to end every episode by arresting a CEO.

00:00:19.334 --> 00:00:22.650
(Nilay laughing)
(upbeat music)

00:00:22.650 --> 00:00:23.940
- Hello and welcome to "Decoder."

00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:26.580
I'm Nilay Patel,
editor-in-chief of "The Verge."

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.370
No, I'm Kate Cox, senior
producer at "The Verge,"

00:00:29.370 --> 00:00:30.750
and "Decoder" is Nilay's show

00:00:30.750 --> 00:00:32.490
about big ideas and other problems,

00:00:32.490 --> 00:00:35.850
that's why it has his face
and voice all over it.

00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:38.130
My co-producer Nick
Statt and I run this show

00:00:38.130 --> 00:00:40.320
and it is fun for us every year

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:43.920
to bring in Nilay to answer
your audience questions.

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:45.450
Nilay, welcome to "Decoder."

00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:47.700
- I really do not like being the guest.

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:49.050
It's my dream to be the guest.

00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:52.140
I think being the guest
is easier in some way,

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:53.490
but I don't like it.

00:00:53.490 --> 00:00:54.930
- Tough. (laughs)

00:00:54.930 --> 00:00:55.890
- I'm just saying, it's just like

00:00:56.763 --> 00:00:58.740
if you sense the abject
terror, here it is,

00:00:58.740 --> 00:00:59.573
let's go.

00:00:59.573 --> 00:01:02.580
- The "Decoder" team had had quite a year,

00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:04.050
among us personally,

00:01:04.050 --> 00:01:05.730
we've had births, deaths,

00:01:05.730 --> 00:01:08.130
marriages and house purchases.

00:01:08.130 --> 00:01:09.420
We've been very busy.

00:01:09.420 --> 00:01:12.060
We've also been very busy
making you lots of "Decoder"

00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:14.490
that you, the audience, have
had lots of opinions about

00:01:14.490 --> 00:01:18.120
and you have written to us and
we love getting those emails.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:20.670
- We got a lot of
incredibly positive feedback

00:01:20.670 --> 00:01:23.670
over the summer when Nilay
was out for parental leave.

00:01:23.670 --> 00:01:24.630
So thank you for that.

00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:26.700
It was really awesome
to see some other people

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:28.170
in the "Decoder" chair

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:30.330
and to see everybody have
a lot of big thoughts

00:01:30.330 --> 00:01:32.760
on what those guest host
brought to the show,

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:33.780
what we should do differently,

00:01:33.780 --> 00:01:35.130
how we might improve.

00:01:35.130 --> 00:01:36.840
So thank you for those.

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:38.370
- With that said, we're
gonna jump right in

00:01:38.370 --> 00:01:39.630
with some listener questions.

00:01:39.630 --> 00:01:41.070
- Yeah, the first question we have is

00:01:41.070 --> 00:01:43.920
from listener Joe Rodericks.

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:46.500
It's actually a two-part question, Nilay.

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:48.877
The first part is, "Do you
really read all the emails?

00:01:48.877 --> 00:01:50.790
"And that must be exhausting."

00:01:50.790 --> 00:01:53.100
His second question is
he gets a ton of value

00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:54.420
from the "Decoder" questions,

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:57.090
which he's actually
started asking candidates

00:01:57.090 --> 00:01:58.560
in job interviews,

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:00.570
particularly how they make decisions.

00:02:00.570 --> 00:02:02.377
So he says, "I can't believe
I'm going to suggest this,

00:02:02.377 --> 00:02:03.210
"but I'd love it

00:02:03.210 --> 00:02:05.677
"if there were more in-the-weeds
Decoder-type questions

00:02:05.677 --> 00:02:07.830
"about business decision-making."

00:02:07.830 --> 00:02:09.067
So his question is, "Nilay,

00:02:09.067 --> 00:02:10.657
"what questions do you want to add

00:02:10.657 --> 00:02:12.720
"to the 'Decoder' question list?"

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:15.570
- Well, first, I will say
we do read all the emails

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:16.890
and I think we really enjoy reading them.

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:18.840
The promise is that we read them all,

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:20.160
not that we reply to them.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:22.890
That's where the work escalates
to be too hard very quickly.

00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:25.020
But we love reading
them, keep sending them.

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:26.910
They're very useful.

00:02:26.910 --> 00:02:28.440
They shape a lot of the questions I ask

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:30.600
in the episodes afterwards.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:31.440
So just keep sending 'em.

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:33.340
We love 'em, we talk about them a lot.

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:35.640
The "Decoder" questions
are really interesting.

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:36.630
So you know, we started the show,

00:02:36.630 --> 00:02:39.480
I think we're five years into the show now

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:42.720
and podcasts are a forever project,

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:44.850
like, especially interview podcasts.

00:02:44.850 --> 00:02:45.810
Kate and Nick spend a lot of time

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:47.820
trying to get guests to show up.

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:49.200
Like, literally just show up on time

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:50.100
and make their headphones work.

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:52.170
Like that's a lot to do every week

00:02:52.170 --> 00:02:53.460
unless you have some goals.

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:55.530
And so one of my goals
at the very beginning was

00:02:55.530 --> 00:02:58.020
to impose some structure on the show

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:00.360
to try to learn something over time

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:02.100
to make the show,

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:04.650
like, make a promise
to you, the listeners,

00:03:04.650 --> 00:03:05.880
and deliver on that promise every week

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:07.320
so it's not just a forever project

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:08.550
about whatsoever in the news.

00:03:08.550 --> 00:03:09.720
And so that's where they came from.

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:12.720
'Cause I figured I could ask every CEO

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:14.700
how their company was structured
and how they make decisions

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:15.533
and they would have to,

00:03:15.533 --> 00:03:17.460
like, it's not a gotcha question.

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:19.500
The fascinating thing is it turns out

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.030
to be a gotcha question

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:22.830
and I think Kate and Nick,

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:24.600
we all have this experience,

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:27.210
every now and again,
someone is just not prepared

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:28.650
for the "Decoder" questions.

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:30.900
They cannot tell us
how they make decisions

00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:33.450
or most interestingly of all,

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:35.550
they avoid telling us how
their company is structured

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:38.790
because it turns out that's
a very political answer.

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:41.640
So we could add more to it.

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:45.000
I think there's a lot to get
from the "Decoder" questions.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:46.710
There's a "Decoder" book
that's gonna come out,

00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:47.543
that deal is signed.

00:03:47.543 --> 00:03:48.690
I'm not gonna reveal too much about it,

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:50.130
but it's based on those questions.

00:03:50.130 --> 00:03:53.400
And the number one thing I would say is

00:03:53.400 --> 00:03:55.260
it might be interesting for you

00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:57.720
as the person who's hiring or the boss

00:03:57.720 --> 00:03:59.220
to ask the people who work for you,

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:01.530
or might want to work for
you, the "Decoder" questions,

00:04:01.530 --> 00:04:02.970
how they make decisions,

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:05.700
it is vastly more revealing
to go ask your boss

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:09.150
and if your boss can't answer
how they make decisions,

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:11.880
you should run, you should
start applying for a new job.

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:14.640
That might be the biggest
takeaway from doing the show is,

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:17.490
boy, when somebody can't
answer the questions,

00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:18.577
all three of us are like,

00:04:18.577 --> 00:04:22.020
"Oh, this episode is gonna
go totally sideways."

00:04:22.020 --> 00:04:25.140
I know there's deeper in-the-weeds
decision-making questions

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:25.973
we could ask.

00:04:25.973 --> 00:04:27.180
I thought Jon Fortt,

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:29.730
when he interviewed Google's
former chief decision scientist

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:30.750
as a guest episode,

00:04:30.750 --> 00:04:32.280
super fascinating episode

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:33.487
and I thought a lot about,

00:04:33.487 --> 00:04:36.270
"Should I incorporate more
of these kinds of questions."

00:04:36.270 --> 00:04:39.810
But to me, getting the
framework of decisions

00:04:39.810 --> 00:04:41.880
and then putting the
framework into practice

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:43.590
with what's actually
happening in the company

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:44.580
is so revealing.

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:45.990
I don't wanna get away from it.

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:46.920
So I could definitely think of more,

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:50.400
I'm eager for your
contributions or your thoughts,

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:52.530
but actually my suggestion
is go ask your boss

00:04:52.530 --> 00:04:54.960
how they make decisions and
let me know how the answers go.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:57.157
'Cause I think that would be
a fundamentally interesting

00:04:57.157 --> 00:04:58.680
"Decoder" episode all on its own.

00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:00.870
- So should Nick and I be asking
you how you make decisions?

00:05:00.870 --> 00:05:02.460
- I have no framework
for making decisions.

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:05.100
It's all chaos and panic every single day.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:06.000
Sorry, Kate.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:07.495
- That's not, not true actually.

00:05:07.495 --> 00:05:09.870
(Nilay and Kate laughing)

00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:10.770
- So, one of the...

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:12.420
I get asked this question a lot.

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:15.090
I do think about how I make decisions,

00:05:15.090 --> 00:05:17.910
fundamentally, my goal
is to be predictable.

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:19.890
Like, we run a newsroom,

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:21.840
newsrooms have to run really fast.

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:23.610
If I am not predictable

00:05:23.610 --> 00:05:25.560
then all the people who
work in the newsroom

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:27.390
are always, like, destabilized.

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:28.800
All of us have worked in newsrooms before,

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:30.570
we've worked in unstable newsrooms before,

00:05:30.570 --> 00:05:34.170
and like, that is just one of
those things about working...

00:05:34.170 --> 00:05:35.490
Like "The Verge" newsroom operates

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:37.860
in basically 20-minute increments.

00:05:37.860 --> 00:05:40.350
Like, news happens and then
something has to happen

00:05:40.350 --> 00:05:42.720
on our site within 20
minutes for us to be on time.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:44.250
That means I have to
be really predictable.

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:47.130
So, you know, we are always joking

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:48.690
that anybody who's been

00:05:48.690 --> 00:05:51.570
within 1,000 miles of Amazon headquarters

00:05:51.570 --> 00:05:54.630
gets, like, infected like Pluribus,

00:05:54.630 --> 00:05:56.340
you know, like they
all just come out of it

00:05:56.340 --> 00:05:57.600
saying the hive-mind thing

00:05:57.600 --> 00:05:59.400
about type-one and type-two decisions

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:00.990
and the decisions you can make quickly

00:06:00.990 --> 00:06:01.860
'cause you can reverse them,

00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:02.970
and the decisions you can't reverse,

00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:03.803
you have to go slow.

00:06:03.803 --> 00:06:05.370
"The Verge" newsroom is almost entirely

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:07.810
like a type-one decisions newsroom

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:10.500
'cause we just have to go fast.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:11.760
Like, there'll be another story tomorrow,

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:12.610
we can try again.

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:15.180
Type-two decisions for us are like,

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:16.013
what should the product look like?

00:06:16.013 --> 00:06:17.910
You know, like, how should we think

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:18.900
about expanding to YouTube?

00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:20.070
And we did take a lot of time

00:06:20.070 --> 00:06:21.900
to make sure we got that stuff right.

00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:23.777
- Speaking of predictable, CarPlay,

00:06:23.777 --> 00:06:27.060
Nilay, you talk about CarPlay a lot.

00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:28.590
Every time we have a car CEO,

00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:30.390
you ask them about CarPlay.

00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:32.970
We had Joanna Stern guest
hosting for you this summer.

00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:35.730
She asked all our car CEOs about CarPlay.

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:37.350
Also, you personally like cars,

00:06:37.350 --> 00:06:39.753
so we have car CEOs on kind of a lot.

00:06:39.753 --> 00:06:40.586
(Nilay laughing)

00:06:40.586 --> 00:06:42.480
Listeners have a lot
of thought about this.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:45.150
So, for example, listener
Matt McCurdy agrees with you

00:06:45.150 --> 00:06:47.850
and he said he finds it
"infuriating," that's a quote,

00:06:47.850 --> 00:06:50.910
when CEOs don't seem to get
why people want CarPlay.

00:06:50.910 --> 00:06:52.470
This is a very popular sentiment

00:06:52.470 --> 00:06:54.390
in our comments and our inboxes,

00:06:54.390 --> 00:06:55.223
in my house,

00:06:55.223 --> 00:06:57.330
my husband is buying a new
car literally tomorrow,

00:06:57.330 --> 00:07:00.120
CarPlay was one of his top
features that he had to have.

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:02.400
But we also got an email
from listener Joseph Quinn

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:05.640
who wrote to make the case
for CarPlay not being good.

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:07.837
And he wrote "CarPlay
is a bandaid solution

00:07:07.837 --> 00:07:09.637
"to make the best of a bad situation

00:07:09.637 --> 00:07:11.017
"in the majority of cars,

00:07:11.017 --> 00:07:13.447
"and there exists a lot
of legacy entrenchment

00:07:13.447 --> 00:07:15.150
"in that convenience."

00:07:15.150 --> 00:07:16.530
So they're both kind of right.

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:18.517
But the overall question
from the inbox is,

00:07:18.517 --> 00:07:22.110
"Nilay, why do you care
so much about CarPlay?"

00:07:22.110 --> 00:07:23.220
- Well, first, I need to know

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:24.930
what kind of car are you buying?

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:27.003
- Hyundai Elantra Hybrid.
- Oh, sure.

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:29.786
We should just do an entire
episode about hybrids.

00:07:29.786 --> 00:07:32.130
- Yeah, it's replacing a 2011 Civic,

00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:34.110
so, you know.
- Very good.

00:07:34.110 --> 00:07:36.390
No, no CarPlay in the Civic.

00:07:36.390 --> 00:07:37.710
Okay, why do I care about CarPlay?

00:07:37.710 --> 00:07:39.360
I actually don't like CarPlay.

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:41.550
I have it in one car.

00:07:41.550 --> 00:07:42.383
We don't have it.

00:07:42.383 --> 00:07:45.843
Well, you know, we had
Mary Barra on from GM,

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:48.720
I have a Cadillac, it
doesn't have CarPlay.

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:50.010
No one misses it, it's fine.

00:07:50.010 --> 00:07:51.780
I mounted a phone at the end,

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:53.400
it solved its problems.

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:54.450
Why do we talk about it so much?

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:56.130
Why do we pay so much attention to it?

00:07:56.130 --> 00:07:59.520
One, the audience loves it.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:00.870
So that is easy.

00:08:00.870 --> 00:08:04.080
The numbers on CarPlay
episodes are so high.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:05.850
It's remarkable to us even.

00:08:05.850 --> 00:08:07.857
Two, I like a fight

00:08:07.857 --> 00:08:10.350
and CarPlay is just a huge fight

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:13.290
and you can see the contours of the fight

00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:16.740
if you've paid attention
to computers at all

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:17.820
over the past 20 years.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:19.470
Who gets to own the interface?

00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:21.390
Who gets to own the apps?

00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:24.180
Who gets to take 30% out of
every single thing you buy

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:25.650
on this interface?

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:27.030
And historically, the
answer has been Apple.

00:08:27.030 --> 00:08:28.830
I think Apple wants to
keep winning that fight.

00:08:28.830 --> 00:08:33.360
The car makers all know that
they should not give up control

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:36.630
of things like maps to Apple and Google.

00:08:36.630 --> 00:08:38.910
They all know that they're bad at it

00:08:38.910 --> 00:08:39.900
and they're losing ground

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:42.180
to companies like Tesla
who are good at it.

00:08:42.180 --> 00:08:45.180
Upstarts like Rivian think
they will be good at it.

00:08:45.180 --> 00:08:46.620
And then they are also making deals

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:48.090
with Google to provide maps

00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:49.590
'cause they're not gonna
be good at making maps.

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:53.880
And so you just get 500
different competing interests

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:55.860
all in a screen,

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:57.690
in an interface people
can see and understand

00:08:57.690 --> 00:08:59.490
and have feelings about.

00:08:59.490 --> 00:09:01.140
And that's very unusual in tech.

00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:04.170
Like, I would love to do 50
episodes on the Fediverse

00:09:04.170 --> 00:09:06.840
but I can't make you
care about the Fediverse.

00:09:06.840 --> 00:09:09.240
Like, there has to be a
thing that you care about,

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:11.310
and people are very passionate about cars

00:09:11.310 --> 00:09:13.740
and they're very passionate
about CarPlay oddly,

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:16.290
again, they're not passionate
about Android Auto,

00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:17.820
they're passionate about CarPlay.

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:20.520
And so you just see here's this fight,

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:22.440
this clash of titans

00:09:22.440 --> 00:09:24.330
and in the center of it

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:26.700
is something consumers care about a lot.

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:28.470
So I personally agree
with Joseph Quinn here

00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:30.090
who says CarPlay is a crutch.

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:31.260
It is a crutch

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:33.180
and it's a crutch because
the car makers are lazy

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:36.270
and they allowed Apple this
big inroad into their product

00:09:36.270 --> 00:09:37.230
and Apple's not giving up,

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:38.580
and the consumers aren't giving up,

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:39.450
and they've gotta make something

00:09:39.450 --> 00:09:41.190
that's good enough for
you to not want that.

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:42.330
Can they do that?

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:43.920
I do not know the answer to that question.

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:44.910
I think a lot of you think

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:45.900
you know the answer to that question

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:47.550
and the answer is obviously no.

00:09:47.550 --> 00:09:49.050
But there are improvements,

00:09:49.050 --> 00:09:51.690
there is a lot of
incentive to figure it out

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:53.430
and that's why we keep talking about it

00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:56.520
because honestly,
getting a CEO on the show

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:57.727
and saying, "Have you
looked at your own product?

00:09:57.727 --> 00:09:58.650
"It's not good,"

00:09:58.650 --> 00:10:02.370
is like the prototype of a
great episode of "Decoder."

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:03.240
This is why I keep wanting

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:04.920
enterprise software CEOs in the show

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:06.180
and why they don't come.

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:07.980
But car makers love talking to other cars,

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:09.360
they love talking to me for some reason,

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:11.257
and saying, "Is your software good?

00:10:11.257 --> 00:10:12.750
"Really?" is like, that's it.

00:10:12.750 --> 00:10:14.010
I can do that for an hour every week

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:15.870
for the rest of my life.

00:10:15.870 --> 00:10:19.470
- So we've gotten a bunch
of good topic suggestions

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:21.000
from listeners.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:22.680
One of them, Laura Cracknell,

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:25.470
is a librarian in the U.K.

00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:27.420
She says she would love
for "Decoder" to talk

00:10:27.420 --> 00:10:28.920
to some information professionals

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:31.380
about what it's like
in the current moment.

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:33.577
She says, "Libraries are where
lots of normal people end up

00:10:33.577 --> 00:10:35.047
"for tech support and computing.

00:10:35.047 --> 00:10:36.457
"They're a vital lifeline for people

00:10:36.457 --> 00:10:38.377
"who might not have digital access.

00:10:38.377 --> 00:10:40.830
"They're also at the front
line of the free speech war."

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:42.967
She's also writing that, "In particular,

00:10:42.967 --> 00:10:43.957
"in the U.S. right now,

00:10:43.957 --> 00:10:45.817
"public libraries are under siege

00:10:45.817 --> 00:10:47.257
"and they're a canary in the coal mine

00:10:47.257 --> 00:10:49.200
"for the health of democracy."

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:51.690
So, Nilay, are you interested

00:10:51.690 --> 00:10:53.730
in doing any episodes on libraries

00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:55.870
or free access to information?

00:10:55.870 --> 00:10:57.120
- Yeah, I think we should definitely do

00:10:57.120 --> 00:10:58.410
an episode on libraries.

00:10:58.410 --> 00:11:00.570
I think that fascinating dynamic

00:11:00.570 --> 00:11:03.150
of, like, Silicon Valley
continuing to invent public goods

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:05.760
and accidentally inventing
libraries over and over again

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:07.260
is at the heart of all that.

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:11.430
Like, what does it mean to
have, like, the internet

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:13.500
and access to information as a public good

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:15.180
in the commons supported by the state.

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:18.210
Like, boy, there's a lot of
"Decoder" themes in there

00:11:18.210 --> 00:11:19.950
and it is under a lot of pressure.

00:11:19.950 --> 00:11:21.510
I think the framing question I would ask

00:11:21.510 --> 00:11:24.360
and I welcome the help on this is

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:27.330
how do you make the importance
of a library in a community

00:11:27.330 --> 00:11:29.867
legible to people who
might not be going, right?

00:11:29.867 --> 00:11:32.520
'Cause it's important
whether or not you're going,

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:34.530
it's important that there's
a place for people to gather.

00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:36.840
It's important that
communities just express

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:39.570
that they care about knowledge
in that specific way.

00:11:39.570 --> 00:11:41.520
But a lot of people aren't going, right?

00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:43.500
And so finding a way to make that turn

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:45.420
seems really important to me.

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:47.970
I'm interested for the feedback
'cause I could use the help.

00:11:47.970 --> 00:11:49.920
- I have a friend in Los
Angeles whose job that is

00:11:49.920 --> 00:11:52.680
and I think she's about to get yoinked

00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:55.530
into helping me with my job.
- Oh, very good.

00:11:55.530 --> 00:11:57.840
- Steven Ebsurry, who's
a frequent correspondent,

00:11:57.840 --> 00:11:59.880
writes that he would love
to see us do something

00:11:59.880 --> 00:12:02.850
on the ever-increasing issue
of digital identity online,

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:06.840
age verification privacy with
adult sites and social media.

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:09.090
Ben Cooper suggested
we should have folks on

00:12:09.090 --> 00:12:10.980
to talk about the tech scene in India

00:12:10.980 --> 00:12:13.140
and ask if maybe the next Xiaomi or Baidu

00:12:13.140 --> 00:12:14.370
might be coming out of India,

00:12:14.370 --> 00:12:15.420
which is interesting.

00:12:16.290 --> 00:12:18.180
David Jarman actually just sent us a link

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:21.810
about the world's oldest
known org chart from 1855,

00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:23.523
which was just very cool.

00:12:24.570 --> 00:12:25.530
All of these, Nilay,

00:12:25.530 --> 00:12:29.070
so when it comes to
explainer topics, not guests,

00:12:29.070 --> 00:12:31.080
we'll come back to that, I promise,

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:34.230
what would you like us to cover in 2026?

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:35.310
- I gotta see this org chart.

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:37.020
Also, I have to believe
there are org charts

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:38.119
older than 1855.

00:12:38.119 --> 00:12:38.952
- I don't know,

00:12:38.952 --> 00:12:41.490
they claim it's the the
world's oldest org chart,

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:43.530
but maybe it's just
Britain's oldest org chart

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:45.930
'cause it was a British museum.

00:12:45.930 --> 00:12:47.850
- Yeah, you don't think
some, like, Roman emperor

00:12:47.850 --> 00:12:49.380
had, like, an org chart written down,

00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:51.300
and like Claudius is cool, (laughs)

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:54.418
you know, like, it's there.

00:12:54.418 --> 00:12:56.400
I know, I know that there's
an older one than that.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:57.570
We should do that video. That'd be fun.

00:12:57.570 --> 00:12:58.440
So we should just do that one

00:12:58.440 --> 00:12:59.430
and like, what is an org chart,

00:12:59.430 --> 00:13:00.263
where they come from?

00:13:00.263 --> 00:13:01.353
I think that's fascinating.

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:04.230
The other two are,

00:13:04.230 --> 00:13:06.120
we're gonna do a lot of digital identity

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:06.953
on "The Verge" this year

00:13:06.953 --> 00:13:09.090
and I think that will turn
into "Decoder" episodes

00:13:09.090 --> 00:13:10.110
over and over again.

00:13:10.110 --> 00:13:13.380
Tim Cook is in D.C. this
week and the week before,

00:13:13.380 --> 00:13:17.370
lobbying against app stores
having to do age verification.

00:13:17.370 --> 00:13:19.680
He does not want that
to be his responsibility

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:21.390
that runs right into

00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:23.010
do these platform
providers know who you are,

00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:25.260
which runs right into identity,

00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:26.467
at the same time, Tim Cook is like,

00:13:26.467 --> 00:13:29.077
"Put your driver's license into my phone,

00:13:29.077 --> 00:13:30.600
"put your passport into the phone."

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:32.497
Like, "I wanna get rid of your wallet

00:13:32.497 --> 00:13:34.200
"but I don't want to know who you are"

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:37.410
is a very weird product stance to have

00:13:37.410 --> 00:13:40.440
and that's Apple's
product stance right now.

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:42.240
So I think we're gonna do a lot here.

00:13:42.240 --> 00:13:45.510
You can see country by
country, state by state,

00:13:45.510 --> 00:13:46.590
there are so many laws

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:48.000
that depend on knowing how old you are

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.590
and what content you should access.

00:13:49.590 --> 00:13:51.360
Australia just banned
everybody under the age of 16

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:52.650
from having social media.

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:54.750
They need to know who you are.

00:13:54.750 --> 00:13:55.890
So we're gonna see a lot there

00:13:55.890 --> 00:13:57.570
because the internet, as we know it,

00:13:57.570 --> 00:14:00.660
is built on anonymity for
a lot of very good reasons.

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:04.350
There's a lot of surveillance
implications to changing that.

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:06.450
So I can pretty much guarantee

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:09.690
we'll end up doing a bunch of
identity and age verification,

00:14:09.690 --> 00:14:12.780
age laws in the context of kids' safety

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:14.070
on "Decoder" in 2026.

00:14:14.070 --> 00:14:17.070
That seems like a promise
we can make, right, guys?

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:19.170
The India topic is ultra fascinating.

00:14:19.170 --> 00:14:20.850
Obviously, all the big
tech companies are there.

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:22.710
They've spun off a lot
of their own talent.

00:14:22.710 --> 00:14:24.630
There's a lot of money in India.

00:14:24.630 --> 00:14:26.220
The question of whether India can make

00:14:26.220 --> 00:14:30.390
its own giant, multinational,
global tech firm

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:32.100
on the order of a Baidu or something

00:14:32.100 --> 00:14:34.830
kind of runs into India's own nationalism,

00:14:34.830 --> 00:14:39.240
America's nationalism,
weird Chinese geopolitics

00:14:39.240 --> 00:14:42.180
that gets weirder day by
day from what I can tell.

00:14:42.180 --> 00:14:43.710
We should do that episode.

00:14:43.710 --> 00:14:47.130
It will take us a while to
settle on a theme for that one

00:14:47.130 --> 00:14:49.230
because there's so many issues at play

00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:53.220
about whether that's possible
today in 2026, right?

00:14:53.220 --> 00:14:54.210
If you'd asked me five years ago,

00:14:54.210 --> 00:14:55.890
I'd say obviously, this is gonna happen.

00:14:55.890 --> 00:14:57.720
There's a bunch of Google
millionaires in India

00:14:57.720 --> 00:14:59.640
who are gonna start companies.

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:03.780
But can you start a new
kind of multinational today?

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:04.710
Big question.

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:05.543
- But also the question was

00:15:05.543 --> 00:15:08.340
do you have other explainers
you would like us to?

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:09.750
- Oh, (laughs)

00:15:09.750 --> 00:15:10.680
you know, I'm gonna come back

00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:13.380
and say I think we should do more episodes

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:17.310
on what is happening to social media.

00:15:17.310 --> 00:15:20.100
What happens when AI slop
overtakes social media?

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:21.990
What happens to the creator industry

00:15:21.990 --> 00:15:23.580
when the supply of content,

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:25.770
because of AI, goes through the roof.

00:15:25.770 --> 00:15:29.430
I predict that the creator
economy is gonna get rocked

00:15:29.430 --> 00:15:30.263
in 2026.

00:15:30.263 --> 00:15:31.260
I basically predict this every year

00:15:31.260 --> 00:15:34.050
but you can see the
cracks starting to form.

00:15:34.050 --> 00:15:36.060
You can see some of the rates
dropping for brand deals,

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:38.430
which I think is really interesting

00:15:38.430 --> 00:15:41.037
and I think the users are
gonna rebel against AI

00:15:41.037 --> 00:15:43.680
and the social networks
are gonna have to do a form

00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:47.130
of really interesting content
moderation to label that stuff

00:15:47.130 --> 00:15:48.720
that they do not want to do.

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:49.740
So I think we're gonna

00:15:49.740 --> 00:15:51.840
find ourselves doing explainer episodes

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:54.780
about content moderation again in '26

00:15:54.780 --> 00:15:56.610
but in the context of AI and creators,

00:15:56.610 --> 00:15:57.600
which will be fascinating.

00:15:57.600 --> 00:15:58.620
- Speaking of AI,

00:15:58.620 --> 00:16:02.730
we have a lot, a lot
of audience questions,

00:16:02.730 --> 00:16:05.220
and feedback, and thoughts

00:16:05.220 --> 00:16:09.150
about how much we have discussed
AI on "Decoder" this year.

00:16:09.150 --> 00:16:12.390
- Yeah, I would say it was
probably the number one topic

00:16:12.390 --> 00:16:14.253
for feedback we got all year long.

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:19.380
Probably the second one was
"Don't talk about Trump so much"

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:20.213
in the beginning of the year,

00:16:20.213 --> 00:16:23.100
and then it turned into
"Don't talk about AI so much."

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:24.810
Yeah, we got a lot of feedback about AI.

00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:26.910
People angry at AI,

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:28.980
people who don't want
us to feature it at all,

00:16:28.980 --> 00:16:30.660
people who want us to only feature it

00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:32.439
and light it on fire and
burn it to the ground.

00:16:32.439 --> 00:16:33.420
(Nilay laughing)

00:16:33.420 --> 00:16:35.220
There was just a lot going on

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:37.950
in the AI space this year, of course.

00:16:37.950 --> 00:16:39.930
We got a lot of positive feedback about,

00:16:39.930 --> 00:16:42.600
for instance, Liz Lappato's
CoreWeave feature,

00:16:42.600 --> 00:16:45.450
which we featured an episode on.

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:48.120
We got a lot of feedback about
Alex Heath's guest hosting

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:49.920
and Casey Newton's guest
hosting this summer,

00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:52.530
which our listeners felt
they weren't critical enough

00:16:52.530 --> 00:16:54.000
of the AI industry,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.210
which I'm sure they hear
that enough on their own.

00:16:57.210 --> 00:16:59.880
We got a lot of feedback
about Hayden Field's episodes

00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:03.000
where she talked about AI in the military

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:04.770
and how the AI industry is cozying up

00:17:04.770 --> 00:17:06.870
to the military industrial complex.

00:17:06.870 --> 00:17:10.650
We also got a lot of positive
feedback about Jon Fortt,

00:17:10.650 --> 00:17:11.820
a guest host this summer,

00:17:11.820 --> 00:17:14.280
interview with author Gil Duran

00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:16.470
who writes a newsletter
called "The Nerd Reich."

00:17:16.470 --> 00:17:18.870
He specifically criticized figures

00:17:18.870 --> 00:17:20.820
like Elon Musk and Peter Thiel

00:17:20.820 --> 00:17:24.300
and kind of their connections
to the Dark Enlightenment

00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:27.330
and kind of how it's all coming
together in the AI industry

00:17:27.330 --> 00:17:28.620
and companies like Palantir

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:30.813
in a way that feels
really scary and weird.

00:17:31.860 --> 00:17:34.290
So yeah, we got kind of the
whole spectrum of feedback

00:17:34.290 --> 00:17:36.330
about covering the AI industry

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:39.210
and kind of by extension
Silicon Valley billionaires

00:17:39.210 --> 00:17:42.540
and what their vision for the future is.

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:47.010
So, Nilay, how do you think
about AI on "Decoder,"

00:17:47.010 --> 00:17:49.140
about covering AI more generally?

00:17:49.140 --> 00:17:51.090
And also the fact that it seems

00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:53.850
like literally every single
CEO we have on the show

00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:55.830
is basically tripping over themselves

00:17:55.830 --> 00:18:00.830
to say AI is the thing that's
going to define our future,

00:18:01.050 --> 00:18:02.730
it's gonna supercharge our businesses

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:04.830
and we have to invest in it

00:18:04.830 --> 00:18:06.960
because if we don't, we're
gonna get left behind.

00:18:06.960 --> 00:18:09.480
- Well, first I'll just say something

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:10.590
that I feel very deeply

00:18:10.590 --> 00:18:12.900
about the fact that we run a newsroom,

00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:16.140
ignoring things does
not make them go away.

00:18:16.140 --> 00:18:18.930
And so we could just do
CarPlay episodes every week

00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:20.160
for the rest of the year.

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:21.750
The AI industry is not gonna stop.

00:18:21.750 --> 00:18:23.430
What we bring to the table,

00:18:23.430 --> 00:18:26.010
ideally as a publication, as a show,

00:18:26.010 --> 00:18:29.430
is a little bit of critical
distance from the hype

00:18:29.430 --> 00:18:31.530
and the ability to have these people on

00:18:31.530 --> 00:18:33.690
and ask them the questions.

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:35.070
I talked about the people

00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:36.840
who can and cannot answer
the "Decoder" questions.

00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:37.890
I invite you to go back

00:18:37.890 --> 00:18:40.530
and see how revealing
some of those answers are

00:18:40.530 --> 00:18:43.530
in this context, in the
context of the AI question.

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:44.820
'Cause I learned a lot.

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:46.200
And so I like to show my work.

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:48.540
I like very much to say,

00:18:48.540 --> 00:18:50.137
like, "I've asked the questions,

00:18:50.137 --> 00:18:51.210
"I have my opinions,"

00:18:51.210 --> 00:18:53.340
it's based on the fact that
I've done the reporting.

00:18:53.340 --> 00:18:54.990
You can evaluate the reporting.

00:18:54.990 --> 00:18:56.820
Maybe you think I'm too soft too,

00:18:56.820 --> 00:18:58.170
but at least you can
evaluate the reporting.

00:18:58.170 --> 00:19:00.000
So that's just the first piece.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.970
I don't think me personally
ignoring the AI industry

00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:04.530
will make it go away or stop.

00:19:04.530 --> 00:19:06.480
And I don't think me
paying attention to it

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:09.090
or us paying attention to it
accelerates it in any way.

00:19:09.090 --> 00:19:10.350
I really just don't think

00:19:10.350 --> 00:19:12.210
that's the function of our newsroom.

00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:13.140
We cover technology

00:19:13.140 --> 00:19:18.140
and I fundamentally believe
that there is something about AI

00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:21.510
that will create a new set of products.

00:19:21.510 --> 00:19:22.343
And I say this

00:19:22.343 --> 00:19:25.440
only because every single day
we are pitched some products

00:19:25.440 --> 00:19:28.050
built on the enabling technology of AI.

00:19:28.050 --> 00:19:31.110
Do I think LLMs can get to AGI,

00:19:31.110 --> 00:19:31.943
I do not.

00:19:31.943 --> 00:19:32.776
We have published that piece.

00:19:32.776 --> 00:19:34.950
It's fascinating, it's called
"Large Language Mistake,"

00:19:34.950 --> 00:19:35.783
it's by Ben Riley.

00:19:35.783 --> 00:19:36.960
It's very interesting.

00:19:36.960 --> 00:19:40.290
I think there's some hard
limits on what LLMs can do

00:19:40.290 --> 00:19:43.620
and I've asked a lot of our
guests about those limits.

00:19:43.620 --> 00:19:45.690
I asked Sundar Pichai if he
thinks language is the same

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:46.860
as intelligence on the show

00:19:46.860 --> 00:19:49.530
and he was like, "Why are
you doing this to me?"

00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:51.810
So I want to keep asking that question.

00:19:51.810 --> 00:19:54.360
Underneath that are a lot of
really interesting questions

00:19:54.360 --> 00:19:57.300
about how will the web work if
you actually make agents go,

00:19:57.300 --> 00:19:59.400
how will anyone get paid?

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:01.350
How are you gonna think about labor?

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:03.030
What is the next interface?

00:20:03.030 --> 00:20:05.370
I said I like a fight in
the context of CarPlay,

00:20:05.370 --> 00:20:07.500
if you really think
natural language interface

00:20:07.500 --> 00:20:09.930
is gonna dominate the computing industry,

00:20:09.930 --> 00:20:12.300
there's a lot of questions
downstream of that.

00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:13.530
Then there's just the opening question,

00:20:13.530 --> 00:20:15.000
is that a good idea?

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.370
So I think we're gonna keep covering AI,

00:20:17.370 --> 00:20:19.290
it's not going anywhere.

00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:22.200
Our attention or ignorance of it

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:24.540
is not gonna affect the
arc of that industry.

00:20:24.540 --> 00:20:26.640
I think what we can get is smarter

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:28.950
about what's real and what's hype.

00:20:28.950 --> 00:20:31.500
And you might disagree with me,

00:20:31.500 --> 00:20:33.000
I know a lot of people disagree with me,

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.940
but this isn't to me the same as crypto,

00:20:35.940 --> 00:20:37.410
which we have all but ignored

00:20:37.410 --> 00:20:40.110
because it's boring and not useful, right?

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:41.820
Like, I don't know what
else to say about that.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:44.070
We've made that point on the
show as many times as we can.

00:20:44.070 --> 00:20:45.840
It's kind of boring and not useful.

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:47.850
AI doesn't feel that to me.

00:20:47.850 --> 00:20:49.950
There's parts of it that are super hypey,

00:20:49.950 --> 00:20:51.630
there's parts of it where Palantir exists,

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:53.010
and Palantir's business innovation,

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:54.300
as far as I can tell,

00:20:54.300 --> 00:20:56.950
is just they will do immoral stuff

00:20:57.912 --> 00:21:01.530
and they'll take some
warmed-over database tech

00:21:01.530 --> 00:21:03.690
and then do stuff that
no one else would do.

00:21:03.690 --> 00:21:05.370
I don't know, we're trying to
have Alex Karp in the show.

00:21:05.370 --> 00:21:08.070
I'm gonna ask him that question
if I can get ahold of him.

00:21:08.070 --> 00:21:09.900
We'll see what happens.

00:21:09.900 --> 00:21:11.700
But the core technology,

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:12.960
the piece of the puzzle

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:16.230
where you as a user can
just talk to the computer

00:21:16.230 --> 00:21:19.080
and the computer can take some actions

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:22.800
or instead of APIs will have MCP servers

00:21:22.800 --> 00:21:24.930
and the agents can just
query a database in natural,

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:27.210
like, there's something there

00:21:27.210 --> 00:21:29.850
that is going to build a
new class of applications.

00:21:29.850 --> 00:21:34.440
I think it is very important
to pay critical attention to it

00:21:34.440 --> 00:21:36.570
and figure out what's
real and what's fake.

00:21:36.570 --> 00:21:37.710
So we're gonna keep doing it.

00:21:37.710 --> 00:21:39.240
Again, I don't think the technology

00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:41.130
that we have today gets you to AGI

00:21:41.130 --> 00:21:44.670
and I think saying that that's
wrong over and over again

00:21:44.670 --> 00:21:47.730
is, like, part of the
promise I will make to you.

00:21:47.730 --> 00:21:50.550
But everything up to that is,
like, I think up for grabs

00:21:50.550 --> 00:21:52.380
and I think there's a
lot of just interest,

00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:57.180
young developers, new
companies, new structures

00:21:57.180 --> 00:22:00.720
that are fascinating that
we should pay attention to

00:22:00.720 --> 00:22:03.810
beyond just talking to the
CEOs of the thing companies

00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:04.950
over and over again.

00:22:04.950 --> 00:22:09.240
- One specific AI challenge
we discussed this year.

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:11.700
We had your episode on
the DoorDash problem

00:22:11.700 --> 00:22:14.610
and you specifically asked
our listeners and viewers

00:22:14.610 --> 00:22:16.860
to write into us what their thoughts,

00:22:16.860 --> 00:22:19.113
and dozens of them did
what you told them to.

00:22:19.950 --> 00:22:23.220
We have a few really
interesting pieces of feedback

00:22:23.220 --> 00:22:24.570
about the DoorDash problem.

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:28.050
So Angela Diffly, who said
she's a director at Coca-Cola,

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:31.297
she said, "I believe Perplexity
has a fighting chance

00:22:31.297 --> 00:22:32.617
"against Amazon.

00:22:32.617 --> 00:22:34.117
"Here's the tension,

00:22:34.117 --> 00:22:37.237
"restaurants currently
lose up to 30% margin

00:22:37.237 --> 00:22:40.447
"to delivery giants like
DoorDash and Uber Eats.

00:22:40.447 --> 00:22:41.287
"They've been clawing

00:22:41.287 --> 00:22:43.537
"to bring customers back
to native platforms,

00:22:43.537 --> 00:22:45.930
"not just for margin but for data."

00:22:45.930 --> 00:22:48.967
She asks, "If AI-driven
ordering agents take over,

00:22:48.967 --> 00:22:51.097
"will restaurants finally win

00:22:51.097 --> 00:22:54.457
"or just continue to lose margin
to the next big disruptor?

00:22:54.457 --> 00:22:56.730
"And when delivery becomes autonomous,"

00:22:56.730 --> 00:22:59.587
which is a whole separate
other problem, that is a thing,

00:22:59.587 --> 00:23:03.060
"what happens to the
economics of convenience?

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:05.017
And then Ian Janicki also wrote,

00:23:05.017 --> 00:23:06.517
"You mentioned that retailers

00:23:06.517 --> 00:23:09.247
"could have their customer
connections severed,

00:23:09.247 --> 00:23:11.610
"but is that necessarily bad?

00:23:11.610 --> 00:23:13.657
As consumers, do we actually want

00:23:13.657 --> 00:23:15.277
"to be tracked across the internet

00:23:15.277 --> 00:23:17.797
"just to satisfy a value calculation

00:23:17.797 --> 00:23:22.110
"or isn't agentic shopping
inherently more privacy-first?"

00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:24.960
So it's only been a few weeks
since the DoorDash episode,

00:23:26.100 --> 00:23:28.420
but all of our listeners
would like to know

00:23:29.910 --> 00:23:31.530
from their responses,

00:23:31.530 --> 00:23:33.690
did you hear anything else
that has really surprised you

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:36.090
or changed your thinking on the subject

00:23:36.090 --> 00:23:38.790
in that last few weeks?

00:23:38.790 --> 00:23:41.160
- Yeah, the one very
surprising thing happened

00:23:41.160 --> 00:23:45.030
and I wanna answer our listener questions,

00:23:45.030 --> 00:23:47.490
but the episode on YouTube
kind of broke containment

00:23:47.490 --> 00:23:50.130
and went into the broader
YouTube algorithm a little bit.

00:23:50.130 --> 00:23:51.997
And then the comments were like,

00:23:51.997 --> 00:23:53.580
"I can't believe capitalists talk

00:23:53.580 --> 00:23:55.320
about owning the customer."

00:23:55.320 --> 00:23:57.450
And that, to me, just represents a lot.

00:23:57.450 --> 00:23:58.890
Like "Decoder" is a
little bit of a bubble.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:00.360
It's a business podcast.

00:24:00.360 --> 00:24:02.550
We use business vocabulary,

00:24:02.550 --> 00:24:05.730
we used acronyms, like,
we're in the bubble

00:24:05.730 --> 00:24:06.990
of how do you run a business

00:24:06.990 --> 00:24:08.550
and how do you make money on the internet?

00:24:08.550 --> 00:24:12.030
And then you break containment
on an algorithmic platform

00:24:12.030 --> 00:24:13.440
and a bunch of people hear you talk

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:14.910
about owning the customer

00:24:14.910 --> 00:24:16.620
and they're like, "This is horrible."

00:24:16.620 --> 00:24:18.960
Like, "I don't wish to
be owned in this way."

00:24:18.960 --> 00:24:22.740
And I think there's something
very important there, right?

00:24:22.740 --> 00:24:24.300
I don't think people want to feel

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:25.890
like they're a customer that's owned,

00:24:25.890 --> 00:24:28.170
that, you know, the idea that
you're perfectly surveilled,

00:24:28.170 --> 00:24:30.240
that there's dynamic
pricing on DoorDash now,

00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:31.920
people hate this.

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:33.690
Something very important there.

00:24:33.690 --> 00:24:37.500
Can your own personal LLM
insulate you from that

00:24:37.500 --> 00:24:39.600
by going out in the world on your behalf

00:24:39.600 --> 00:24:41.130
and prevent you from being tracked

00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:43.230
and deal with the restaurants directly?

00:24:43.230 --> 00:24:45.180
'Cause they've set up their
own little MCP servers.

00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:46.620
That would be the dream.

00:24:46.620 --> 00:24:47.853
Is that likely?

00:24:48.870 --> 00:24:50.280
Right, like, is it likely

00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:53.820
that we will all have our
own little agent server

00:24:53.820 --> 00:24:55.890
in the basement running on a Raspberry Pi

00:24:55.890 --> 00:24:58.440
and every restaurant is
gonna have an MCP server

00:24:58.440 --> 00:25:00.540
and there's gonna be
an MCP discovery engine

00:25:00.540 --> 00:25:01.800
that's decentralized.

00:25:01.800 --> 00:25:02.670
Man, I hope so.

00:25:02.670 --> 00:25:04.170
If you are building any of those products,

00:25:04.170 --> 00:25:05.310
you give us a call,

00:25:05.310 --> 00:25:06.750
we will pay so much attention to you

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:09.003
that you have no choice
but to be successful.

00:25:10.200 --> 00:25:13.350
But I don't think that's how
it's gonna work. (laughs)

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:14.277
And the flip side of that,

00:25:14.277 --> 00:25:16.620
and I saw this on the
comments on our site,

00:25:16.620 --> 00:25:17.760
I see this on comments on YouTube,

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:20.370
I think it's reflected in
Angela's comment there,

00:25:20.370 --> 00:25:22.950
people aren't happy with DoorDash, right?

00:25:22.950 --> 00:25:25.800
They're not happy with these
middlemen service providers,

00:25:26.790 --> 00:25:29.670
but those service providers exist, right?

00:25:29.670 --> 00:25:32.760
So if you disrupt Uber,

00:25:32.760 --> 00:25:34.497
if you get rid of Uber,
and Lyft, and DoorDash,

00:25:34.497 --> 00:25:36.180
and whatever else tomorrow,

00:25:36.180 --> 00:25:38.040
a lot of people whose income

00:25:38.040 --> 00:25:41.190
and livelihoods depend on
those platforms get disrupted.

00:25:41.190 --> 00:25:44.190
So you have to make some
trade-offs along the way

00:25:44.190 --> 00:25:46.860
and you can say, "Man, I
wish Uber never existed."

00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:48.870
But the problem is that it does.

00:25:48.870 --> 00:25:51.480
Like, I can't do anything
about that for you.

00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:53.227
So it exists and now you're saying,

00:25:53.227 --> 00:25:55.560
"Okay, it could change
and could get disrupted."

00:25:55.560 --> 00:25:57.180
All the people who make their living

00:25:57.180 --> 00:25:58.560
driving for Uber today,

00:25:58.560 --> 00:25:59.970
what are you gonna do with them?

00:25:59.970 --> 00:26:02.820
And so maybe the 30% should
move back to the restaurants,

00:26:02.820 --> 00:26:04.710
but now you've taken away
from the Uber drivers

00:26:04.710 --> 00:26:06.450
and you've moved it to robots,

00:26:06.450 --> 00:26:08.490
that is a trade-off you could make.

00:26:08.490 --> 00:26:11.100
The technology could force us
into that trade-off over time.

00:26:11.100 --> 00:26:14.310
But I think our show is
gonna just put people

00:26:14.310 --> 00:26:15.990
in the complicated situation

00:26:15.990 --> 00:26:18.270
of having to make those trade-offs

00:26:18.270 --> 00:26:19.860
or at least work through those trade-offs

00:26:19.860 --> 00:26:21.480
over the course of an hour-long interview.

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:23.160
'Cause it's all coming.

00:26:23.160 --> 00:26:25.170
And I don't think the agents,

00:26:25.170 --> 00:26:27.090
they're not gonna live in our
basements on Raspberry Pis.

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:29.340
They're gonna live on big,
centralized cloud services

00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:32.190
operated by tech giants who
have their own incentives.

00:26:32.190 --> 00:26:34.470
Understanding their
incentives versus your own

00:26:34.470 --> 00:26:36.120
will be, I think, critical

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:38.370
to preserving some consumer agency.

00:26:38.370 --> 00:26:40.890
- One listener, Asif Saggi,

00:26:40.890 --> 00:26:42.450
wrote in about your prediction last year

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:45.150
related to the economy, Nilay.

00:26:45.150 --> 00:26:46.740
So you brought it up a little bit earlier

00:26:46.740 --> 00:26:48.780
that you are kind of always keeping an eye

00:26:48.780 --> 00:26:49.770
on the creator economy,

00:26:49.770 --> 00:26:51.720
what might happen to it.

00:26:51.720 --> 00:26:54.670
He's asking specifically, "Do you think

00:26:54.670 --> 00:26:57.277
"that with AI dominating
the industry right now,

00:26:57.277 --> 00:27:01.237
"will we even notice or hear
the creator bubble bursting

00:27:01.237 --> 00:27:02.617
"or do you think the creator economy

00:27:02.617 --> 00:27:04.980
"has already corrected itself?"

00:27:04.980 --> 00:27:06.360
- I think there's been some correction

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:08.460
in the creator economy already.

00:27:08.460 --> 00:27:11.160
Let me be specific
about what I mean there.

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:14.430
The creator economy is really expressed

00:27:14.430 --> 00:27:16.470
as brands can show up,

00:27:16.470 --> 00:27:20.040
pay creators to do
endorsements and sponsorships

00:27:20.040 --> 00:27:22.640
and that will drive some
sales back to those brands.

00:27:23.490 --> 00:27:24.540
That's the whole economy.

00:27:24.540 --> 00:27:26.040
There's not a part of that economy

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:28.170
where any of the platforms

00:27:28.170 --> 00:27:30.990
are paying creators high
enough rates to survive.

00:27:30.990 --> 00:27:32.314
So if you are a YouTuber,

00:27:32.314 --> 00:27:35.280
or an Instagram influencer, or a TikToker,

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:36.117
YouTube, Instagram, and TikTok

00:27:36.117 --> 00:27:39.720
are not paying you nearly
enough money to eat.

00:27:39.720 --> 00:27:41.280
It's just not true.

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:42.960
And so all of those creators

00:27:42.960 --> 00:27:45.390
need to get subsidized by brands.

00:27:45.390 --> 00:27:47.250
They need to do brand
deals and sponsorships

00:27:47.250 --> 00:27:48.930
and find other ways to make money,

00:27:48.930 --> 00:27:51.510
'cause the platforms
themselves don't pay enough.

00:27:51.510 --> 00:27:54.240
And this is the heart
of the creator economy.

00:27:54.240 --> 00:27:55.680
The platforms don't pay enough money

00:27:55.680 --> 00:27:57.390
to support the content of the platforms.

00:27:57.390 --> 00:27:59.760
So advertising has to fill in the gap.

00:27:59.760 --> 00:28:02.310
And what you're seeing this year is

00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:06.210
the advertisers are not paying
the same rates as they were,

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:07.620
particularly in like the pandemic

00:28:07.620 --> 00:28:08.670
when rates shot through the roof

00:28:08.670 --> 00:28:10.050
'cause no one can measure anything.

00:28:10.050 --> 00:28:12.030
The advertisers are getting smarter

00:28:12.030 --> 00:28:15.600
about the return their
money is delivering.

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:17.250
So you can't just pay every creator,

00:28:17.250 --> 00:28:18.810
you can actually start
to measure creators.

00:28:18.810 --> 00:28:21.240
We had the CEO of SharkNinja on the show

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:23.220
and he said they do very
sophisticated measurement

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:24.510
of engagement.

00:28:24.510 --> 00:28:25.410
They don't just want views,

00:28:25.410 --> 00:28:26.820
they want likes and comments.

00:28:26.820 --> 00:28:29.640
They're doing sentiment
analysis on the comments

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:30.900
on the videos the creators do

00:28:30.900 --> 00:28:32.490
to promote SharkNinja products

00:28:32.490 --> 00:28:34.560
to figure out what creators
to work with over time

00:28:34.560 --> 00:28:36.060
in a relationship.

00:28:36.060 --> 00:28:37.830
That means rates are dropping, right?

00:28:37.830 --> 00:28:39.780
You're now measuring,
you're paying for results.

00:28:39.780 --> 00:28:42.900
The inevitable result of
metrics is you drop rates

00:28:42.900 --> 00:28:46.320
'cause you're not paying
the the margin for unknowns,

00:28:46.320 --> 00:28:47.580
you're only paying for what you want.

00:28:47.580 --> 00:28:49.410
That's fascinating to me.

00:28:49.410 --> 00:28:50.730
Then you have just the reality

00:28:50.730 --> 00:28:52.320
of SharkNinja is going
to a bunch of creators

00:28:52.320 --> 00:28:54.780
and saying, "We're gonna pay
for exactly this result,"

00:28:54.780 --> 00:28:57.480
and you have turned all
these platforms into QVC,

00:28:57.480 --> 00:28:59.190
and audience engagement might drop.

00:28:59.190 --> 00:29:02.580
Then you flood the
platforms with AI content,

00:29:02.580 --> 00:29:04.260
which is, like, pure engagement slop

00:29:04.260 --> 00:29:05.910
that you can make for $0

00:29:05.910 --> 00:29:07.770
and you can drop those rates even farther.

00:29:07.770 --> 00:29:09.277
Then you have Mark Zuckerberg saying,

00:29:09.277 --> 00:29:11.857
"You don't even need to make ad creative,

00:29:11.857 --> 00:29:14.227
"pay us money, we will AI generate you ads

00:29:14.227 --> 00:29:15.510
"and deliver you business results."

00:29:15.510 --> 00:29:17.310
Which is the thing he
said earlier this year.

00:29:17.310 --> 00:29:18.990
I think that's gonna
drop rates even farther.

00:29:18.990 --> 00:29:20.340
So you just see the beginning

00:29:20.340 --> 00:29:22.170
of the pressure on this economy

00:29:22.170 --> 00:29:25.140
where because the platforms
do not value the content,

00:29:25.140 --> 00:29:28.920
they literally do not pay
enough to the creators to eat,

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:30.840
they are wholly dependent on the dynamics

00:29:30.840 --> 00:29:32.490
of the advertising industry.

00:29:32.490 --> 00:29:34.650
And the advertising industry
is both professionalizing

00:29:34.650 --> 00:29:36.750
and industrializing the creator economy

00:29:36.750 --> 00:29:40.410
and dealing with AI like everybody else.

00:29:40.410 --> 00:29:42.600
And all that means is
the rates are dropping,

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:44.490
the rates for a brand deal are dropping

00:29:44.490 --> 00:29:45.810
and the middle class of creators

00:29:45.810 --> 00:29:47.340
is absolutely getting squeezed.

00:29:47.340 --> 00:29:49.650
So I think that will be a theme.

00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:50.880
It was a little bit of our theme

00:29:50.880 --> 00:29:52.050
of our coverage this year.

00:29:52.050 --> 00:29:54.150
It's gonna be a big theme next year.

00:29:54.150 --> 00:29:54.983
And like I said,

00:29:54.983 --> 00:29:56.580
I think the platforms are
gonna have to start labeling

00:29:56.580 --> 00:29:59.190
and filtering AI content for
a huge number of reasons.

00:29:59.190 --> 00:30:01.110
I think a revolt from creators

00:30:01.110 --> 00:30:02.700
is gonna be one of those reasons.

00:30:02.700 --> 00:30:04.680
- That's the AI piece of it all.

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:07.560
That really takes us to
our Monday guest lineups

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:10.980
because we've talked to a
lot of AI CEOs this year

00:30:10.980 --> 00:30:13.770
and also every CEO we've
talked to this year claims

00:30:13.770 --> 00:30:16.470
to be an AI CEO.
- Yeah, without exception.

00:30:16.470 --> 00:30:18.120
- Without exception, all of them.

00:30:19.230 --> 00:30:20.580
The next person we are interviewing

00:30:20.580 --> 00:30:21.420
is also going to do that.

00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:23.040
That's just what they are.

00:30:23.040 --> 00:30:26.160
We get a lot of our
suggestions for who to talk to

00:30:26.160 --> 00:30:27.150
from our audience.

00:30:27.150 --> 00:30:29.580
When we talked to Unity CEO
Matt Bromberg last year,

00:30:29.580 --> 00:30:30.930
that started with a listener email.

00:30:30.930 --> 00:30:32.317
That subject line was literally,

00:30:32.317 --> 00:30:34.350
"Please, interview my boss."

00:30:34.350 --> 00:30:35.520
I loved that.

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:37.170
If you want us to interview your CEO

00:30:37.170 --> 00:30:39.510
so we can ask them how they
make decisions for you,

00:30:39.510 --> 00:30:40.773
absolutely, let us know.

00:30:41.610 --> 00:30:43.710
Recent requests we've
had come into the inbox

00:30:43.710 --> 00:30:46.230
this past couple weeks
include the CEO of Stripe,

00:30:46.230 --> 00:30:48.210
the CEO of Framework Computer,

00:30:48.210 --> 00:30:50.790
AI guy, Geoffrey Hinton,
and Linus Torvalds,

00:30:50.790 --> 00:30:52.230
which are all interesting suggestions.

00:30:52.230 --> 00:30:53.520
We'll see what next year holds.

00:30:53.520 --> 00:30:55.320
- If you can get us Linus
- Yeah, right?

00:30:55.320 --> 00:30:56.400
- Make the call, let's do it.
- Yeah,

00:30:56.400 --> 00:30:58.110
like, let us know please.

00:30:58.110 --> 00:30:58.980
We would love to.

00:30:58.980 --> 00:31:02.720
Last year we had a set of
moonshot guests that was,

00:31:02.720 --> 00:31:03.810
I don't know, last year we said

00:31:03.810 --> 00:31:05.100
maybe we'll wanna talk to Tim Cook

00:31:05.100 --> 00:31:07.200
or maybe we'll wanna talk to Bob Iger.

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.570
I would still really like
us to talk to Bob Iger.

00:31:09.570 --> 00:31:11.520
I wanna know what he's thinking.

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:15.150
Nilay, who do you have on this
year's moonshot guest list?

00:31:15.150 --> 00:31:16.150
- That's a good one.

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:18.690
Yeah, I'm taking Tim Cook off the list.

00:31:18.690 --> 00:31:20.790
I've said this on "The
Vergecast" several times.

00:31:20.790 --> 00:31:23.190
I don't think he has
anything interesting to say,

00:31:23.190 --> 00:31:25.320
or if he does, he won't say it.

00:31:25.320 --> 00:31:27.810
I've watched any number
of Tim Cook interviews

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:29.790
over the past 15 years

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:33.840
and I've yet to think that I
personally can crack the code

00:31:33.840 --> 00:31:35.610
because no one else has.

00:31:35.610 --> 00:31:37.260
So just off the list.

00:31:37.260 --> 00:31:38.403
Like, unless, Tim,

00:31:39.313 --> 00:31:41.570
you wanna blow it up on your
way out the door, you know.

00:31:41.570 --> 00:31:43.860
if you wanna announce you're
leaving Apple on "Decoder,"

00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:44.693
now's the time.

00:31:45.570 --> 00:31:46.680
It's off the list.

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:50.550
Moonshots, actually, I do think
I should do more interviews

00:31:50.550 --> 00:31:54.030
with people I don't agree
with or openly disagree with.

00:31:54.030 --> 00:31:55.620
So Alex Karp is high on my list.

00:31:55.620 --> 00:31:56.490
I have a lot of questions

00:31:56.490 --> 00:31:59.010
about what Palantir's
technology actually is.

00:31:59.010 --> 00:32:00.300
If you watch any interview with him

00:32:00.300 --> 00:32:01.710
or any executive at Palantir,

00:32:01.710 --> 00:32:03.150
they obfuscate the answers

00:32:03.150 --> 00:32:06.840
to what it is they actually
make incredibly hard

00:32:06.840 --> 00:32:09.150
and I don't think you can
get away with that with me.

00:32:09.150 --> 00:32:10.590
So he's high on my list.

00:32:10.590 --> 00:32:13.050
I think we're overdue on Andy Jassy.

00:32:13.050 --> 00:32:15.210
We've had a lot of Amazon
executives on the show.

00:32:15.210 --> 00:32:16.680
I'm dying to know what he thinks

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:18.660
about the future of that business

00:32:18.660 --> 00:32:20.730
in the context of agentic retail,

00:32:20.730 --> 00:32:22.110
and all those questions there,

00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:24.060
in the context of having to spend money

00:32:24.060 --> 00:32:25.650
on data center build-outs.

00:32:25.650 --> 00:32:27.330
Andy Jassy, come on the show.

00:32:27.330 --> 00:32:28.830
Bob Iger, definitely on the list,

00:32:28.830 --> 00:32:31.950
especially now that he's asking Google

00:32:31.950 --> 00:32:35.280
to stop training on Disney IP

00:32:35.280 --> 00:32:37.800
and then he's investing a
billion dollars in OpenAI

00:32:37.800 --> 00:32:39.660
so that they can use Disney IP.

00:32:39.660 --> 00:32:41.220
That seems very backwards.

00:32:41.220 --> 00:32:42.960
I would love to ask him about
the mechanics of that deal

00:32:42.960 --> 00:32:44.100
and what he's thinking there.

00:32:44.100 --> 00:32:45.540
Dario from Anthropic,

00:32:45.540 --> 00:32:47.760
we've done a lot of AI CEOs,

00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:49.740
we should have Dario, we
should have Sam Altman.

00:32:49.740 --> 00:32:51.120
I think Sam Altman is another one

00:32:51.120 --> 00:32:52.627
where asking what his actual plans,

00:32:52.627 --> 00:32:55.020
"Can you describe the structure
of OpenAI, Sam Altman?"

00:32:55.020 --> 00:32:56.340
That's a challenge I'll issue to you.

00:32:56.340 --> 00:32:57.990
This is what this show is for.

00:32:57.990 --> 00:32:59.257
Everyone gets asked
where their org chart is.

00:32:59.257 --> 00:33:01.680
"Can you describe
OpenAI's org chart, Sam?"

00:33:01.680 --> 00:33:02.970
I welcome you on the show.

00:33:02.970 --> 00:33:04.357
And then I have to say this,

00:33:04.357 --> 00:33:07.020
"Vergecast" listeners
know this is on my list,

00:33:07.020 --> 00:33:09.150
FCC Chairman Brendan Carr.

00:33:09.150 --> 00:33:12.270
Have him anywhere, anytime, any place,

00:33:12.270 --> 00:33:14.580
but if Brendan wants to
come on "Decoder" this year,

00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:15.810
I think we have to take the shot.

00:33:15.810 --> 00:33:18.180
I think that will be a
very interesting episode.

00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:19.230
And it's not so much a moonshot,

00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:20.220
we've interviewed her before

00:33:20.220 --> 00:33:21.720
but I actually think Lisa Su from AMD,

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:23.520
we should have her back next year.

00:33:23.520 --> 00:33:26.610
She's in the heart of
the chip conversation.

00:33:26.610 --> 00:33:29.700
She needs to compete for
capacity with TSMC, with Nvidia,

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:32.610
which is a fascinatingly hard challenge.

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:34.200
We should probably get
Jensen on from Nvidia too,

00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:35.460
but I think, actually Lisa,

00:33:35.460 --> 00:33:37.737
every time we've been on
she's been refreshingly candid

00:33:37.737 --> 00:33:40.620
and AMD is, like, mounting
a little bit of a comeback

00:33:40.620 --> 00:33:42.690
and I think that would be a
really good episode next year.

00:33:42.690 --> 00:33:45.810
- That was a perfect segue
into our next question,

00:33:45.810 --> 00:33:48.150
which is about repeat guests.

00:33:48.150 --> 00:33:53.150
In particular, listener Ian
wanted to know how that happens.

00:33:53.520 --> 00:33:54.967
He says, "You often say to a guest

00:33:54.967 --> 00:33:55.800
"at the end of an interview

00:33:55.800 --> 00:33:57.487
"that it'd be great to have them back,

00:33:57.487 --> 00:33:59.137
"but what's your decision-making framework

00:33:59.137 --> 00:34:01.057
"around actually getting them back?

00:34:01.057 --> 00:34:02.947
"Do you wait for a new product, a book?

00:34:02.947 --> 00:34:06.117
"Do you set a reminder, like
the one I have for 2030"

00:34:06.117 --> 00:34:07.980
and this person actually has a reminder,

00:34:07.980 --> 00:34:09.540
a screenshot of their Reminders app

00:34:09.540 --> 00:34:12.577
where they say, "Contact
Nilay Patel and remind him

00:34:12.577 --> 00:34:15.900
"that the Metaverse will
have a great year in 2030."

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:16.890
- That's great.
- So, yeah,

00:34:16.890 --> 00:34:19.050
he wants to know how do
you have a guest back

00:34:19.050 --> 00:34:20.490
and how does it work?

00:34:20.490 --> 00:34:23.340
- I should ask you two because
you two do all the booking.

00:34:23.340 --> 00:34:26.373
My impression of how
"Decoder" works right now is

00:34:26.373 --> 00:34:29.340
that we do very little outbound.

00:34:29.340 --> 00:34:30.390
We have a lot of incoming,

00:34:30.390 --> 00:34:32.310
a lot of people wanna be on the show.

00:34:32.310 --> 00:34:34.530
The joke I keep making is that

00:34:34.530 --> 00:34:37.140
it's a game called Nilay
versus media training,

00:34:37.140 --> 00:34:40.560
which is a game you can win
but also a game you can lose.

00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:42.690
And the fact that it's
a little bit challenging

00:34:42.690 --> 00:34:45.120
makes a lot of very
competitive type A CEOs

00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:46.200
wanna be on the show.

00:34:46.200 --> 00:34:49.020
'Cause they see their
peers either win or lose

00:34:49.020 --> 00:34:50.370
and they think they can do better.

00:34:50.370 --> 00:34:52.080
By the way, this is not like
some secret information.

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:53.820
I say this out loud all the time

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:55.470
and everyone knows this
is how I think of the show

00:34:55.470 --> 00:34:57.630
and everyone keeps showing up.

00:34:57.630 --> 00:34:58.650
So that's great.

00:34:58.650 --> 00:34:59.820
That continues to work.

00:34:59.820 --> 00:35:01.320
There's a piece of the puzzle
which is really interesting.

00:35:01.320 --> 00:35:02.280
I've heard this from a few people,

00:35:02.280 --> 00:35:04.110
I'm curious if anyone
wants to confirm it to us,

00:35:04.110 --> 00:35:06.990
where a lot of times the
executives come on the show

00:35:06.990 --> 00:35:08.880
'cause they wanna prove
to their own employees

00:35:08.880 --> 00:35:10.290
that they can take the heat

00:35:10.290 --> 00:35:11.940
and there's no way to do that

00:35:11.940 --> 00:35:14.160
in, like, the branded content universe

00:35:14.160 --> 00:35:16.470
or the softball interview universe

00:35:16.470 --> 00:35:17.940
or like, the employee town hall.

00:35:17.940 --> 00:35:18.773
Like,

00:35:18.773 --> 00:35:20.340
you can't have your own head
of comms ask you a question

00:35:20.340 --> 00:35:22.230
that amounts to do you
know what you're doing,

00:35:22.230 --> 00:35:23.427
but I'll do that.

00:35:23.427 --> 00:35:25.050
And so, like, there's
something important there.

00:35:25.050 --> 00:35:26.730
So that's one reason
they keep coming back.

00:35:26.730 --> 00:35:31.230
The repeat guests for me are
when someone got a new job,

00:35:31.230 --> 00:35:33.960
when they're the new CEO or
they're the outgoing CEO,

00:35:33.960 --> 00:35:36.300
super fascinating, they're
a little bit more candid.

00:35:36.300 --> 00:35:37.890
They have to make some.

00:35:37.890 --> 00:35:38.850
Anjali Sud, right?

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:40.980
She went from Vimeo to Tubi.

00:35:40.980 --> 00:35:43.140
I love talking to her
about that transition.

00:35:43.140 --> 00:35:45.120
I thought that was one
of our best episodes ever

00:35:45.120 --> 00:35:46.680
'cause she learned a bunch
of stuff at one place

00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:48.690
and she obviously worked at another place.

00:35:48.690 --> 00:35:50.280
She didn't have to pretend

00:35:50.280 --> 00:35:52.410
that everything had gone
well at the previous place.

00:35:52.410 --> 00:35:54.120
Like, she got to be honest
about what she'd learned.

00:35:54.120 --> 00:35:56.430
I think that's an incredible
time to bring someone back.

00:35:56.430 --> 00:36:00.780
And then there are structural
changes in an industry

00:36:00.780 --> 00:36:03.120
that I think are a really good
time to bring people back on.

00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:07.260
So I suspect we will have
Sundar Pichai and Satya Nadella

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:09.400
on the show on a cadence forever

00:36:10.530 --> 00:36:13.350
because there's huge structural changes

00:36:13.350 --> 00:36:15.030
in the industries in which they work.

00:36:15.030 --> 00:36:17.460
They are among the masters of the universe

00:36:17.460 --> 00:36:19.020
and they like explaining

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:21.150
how they are approaching those changes.

00:36:21.150 --> 00:36:22.470
And I like hearing those answers.

00:36:22.470 --> 00:36:25.470
I think you can hear those interviews.

00:36:25.470 --> 00:36:27.960
I obviously disagree with their
answers from time to time,

00:36:27.960 --> 00:36:29.940
but that dynamic is
really important to me.

00:36:29.940 --> 00:36:31.537
Like, "Is there a structural change?

00:36:31.537 --> 00:36:33.720
"Can you walk me through
it in a way that's honest?"

00:36:33.720 --> 00:36:34.560
That's the other time

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:36.570
when I think a repeat
guest is really important.

00:36:36.570 --> 00:36:39.690
Having a car CEO back every six months

00:36:39.690 --> 00:36:41.490
to say they haven't changed
their mind on CarPlay,

00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:44.700
I think is of diminishing value. (laughs)

00:36:44.700 --> 00:36:45.990
So, yeah, big structural changes,

00:36:45.990 --> 00:36:48.180
or new job, new role,

00:36:48.180 --> 00:36:49.500
if you've changed your org chart,

00:36:49.500 --> 00:36:50.640
you've restructured your company.

00:36:50.640 --> 00:36:52.620
I love those episodes

00:36:52.620 --> 00:36:54.630
because there's something
very rich to talk about.

00:36:54.630 --> 00:36:56.430
- I will say you threw
it to us for a second.

00:36:56.430 --> 00:36:59.550
It is much more common for me and Nick

00:36:59.550 --> 00:37:01.357
to tell somebody, "No,
you can't come back.

00:37:01.357 --> 00:37:02.730
"It's too soon,"

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:04.350
than it is for us to have to reach out

00:37:04.350 --> 00:37:06.120
and say, "Will you come back?"
- Yeah.

00:37:06.120 --> 00:37:07.530
- Which I think is interesting.

00:37:07.530 --> 00:37:09.120
I'm glad you mentioned media training,

00:37:09.120 --> 00:37:10.410
Nilay versus media training

00:37:10.410 --> 00:37:14.310
because we had one very
interesting email from Zach Yani

00:37:14.310 --> 00:37:15.907
who wrote, "My honest feedback is

00:37:15.907 --> 00:37:19.417
"that Nilay versus media
training isn't good radio

00:37:19.417 --> 00:37:22.147
"Nilay and the "Decoder" format
are one of the best attempts

00:37:22.147 --> 00:37:23.947
"to make these PR stops interesting

00:37:23.947 --> 00:37:26.917
"with the 'Decoder' questions
and asking hard questions.

00:37:26.917 --> 00:37:27.757
"Occasionally,

00:37:27.757 --> 00:37:29.977
"Nilay even generates a
really interesting moment

00:37:29.977 --> 00:37:32.197
"when he backs them into
a corner hard enough,

00:37:32.197 --> 00:37:34.567
"but by and large this
is not a good format.

00:37:34.567 --> 00:37:35.917
"It was a great experiment.

00:37:35.917 --> 00:37:38.107
"If anyone could have done
it, it would've been Nilay,

00:37:38.107 --> 00:37:41.160
"but media training makes it boring."

00:37:41.160 --> 00:37:42.667
But he adds, "On the other hand,

00:37:42.667 --> 00:37:43.897
"when Nilay talks to people

00:37:43.897 --> 00:37:45.637
"who aren't selling a company vision

00:37:45.637 --> 00:37:47.287
"'Decoder' can really shine.

00:37:47.287 --> 00:37:49.957
"There have been some truly
great episodes of that format

00:37:49.957 --> 00:37:51.367
"and I bet leaning into that

00:37:51.367 --> 00:37:53.910
"could get some even better guests."

00:37:53.910 --> 00:37:56.583
We've talked about this
a lot inside our team.

00:37:57.450 --> 00:38:00.000
Nilay, I would love for our audience

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:03.570
to hear your thoughts on
our Monday guests overall

00:38:03.570 --> 00:38:06.840
and the whole concept of
Nilay versus media training.

00:38:06.840 --> 00:38:09.270
- All right, can I rewind
the clock all the way.

00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:10.620
We do think about this a lot.

00:38:10.620 --> 00:38:12.810
I'm rewinding the clock to the
very beginning of "Decoder"

00:38:12.810 --> 00:38:17.340
and this show started as
Kara Swisher's show, right?

00:38:17.340 --> 00:38:20.730
It was "Recode Decode"
hosted by Kara Swisher.

00:38:20.730 --> 00:38:23.790
And so she went off to do the next thing.

00:38:23.790 --> 00:38:26.700
She graciously said we
could take over the feed.

00:38:26.700 --> 00:38:30.300
And I was like, "I have
to replace Kara Swisher."

00:38:30.300 --> 00:38:31.584
Like, just imagine that.

00:38:31.584 --> 00:38:33.240
Be like, "Oh yeah, I can just do that."

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:35.850
And so I made a list of
all the things Kara did

00:38:35.850 --> 00:38:37.440
that were of value to the audience

00:38:37.440 --> 00:38:39.180
and all the things I could do.

00:38:39.180 --> 00:38:40.740
And there's a whole bunch
of stuff Kara can do

00:38:40.740 --> 00:38:42.180
that I can't do.

00:38:42.180 --> 00:38:45.150
Just you can make that
list and send me your list,

00:38:45.150 --> 00:38:46.050
send me the list of things

00:38:46.050 --> 00:38:47.250
you think Kara can do that I can do

00:38:47.250 --> 00:38:49.890
and I'll tell you if
it's the same as mine.

00:38:49.890 --> 00:38:53.130
And the one thing I could circle that was,

00:38:53.130 --> 00:38:56.790
I can keep this value
to the audience going

00:38:56.790 --> 00:38:59.250
without completely cratering the feed

00:38:59.250 --> 00:39:01.290
and ruining everyone's experience

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:02.820
was I can interview CEOs, right?

00:39:02.820 --> 00:39:03.930
This is where this all started.

00:39:03.930 --> 00:39:07.410
Like, what is Kara delivering
every week on this show

00:39:07.410 --> 00:39:09.960
that I'm gonna rebrand and
try to do something new,

00:39:09.960 --> 00:39:11.497
and instead of being like,

00:39:11.497 --> 00:39:12.480
"Hey, it's totally different now."

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:15.570
Like, I can continue on
with some scrap of value

00:39:15.570 --> 00:39:17.220
and maybe earn your
trust, do something else.

00:39:17.220 --> 00:39:18.053
And it literally was,

00:39:18.053 --> 00:39:20.130
"I can get CEOs to show
up and talk to me."

00:39:20.130 --> 00:39:20.970
There's a lot of reasons for that.

00:39:20.970 --> 00:39:23.430
I think chief among them is

00:39:23.430 --> 00:39:24.750
the version of product review site.

00:39:24.750 --> 00:39:26.820
And every CEO who makes tech products

00:39:26.820 --> 00:39:28.800
wants to be near product reviews.

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:29.880
And I can do that.

00:39:29.880 --> 00:39:31.530
Great, so we can get the CEOs show up

00:39:31.530 --> 00:39:32.363
and talk about product.

00:39:32.363 --> 00:39:33.630
So that was step one.

00:39:33.630 --> 00:39:36.150
And I think that was successful.

00:39:36.150 --> 00:39:37.800
We didn't turn a bunch
of Kara's audience away

00:39:37.800 --> 00:39:40.710
and Kara went off to do all her
amazing things that she does

00:39:40.710 --> 00:39:43.740
and now we're doing
something different, right?

00:39:43.740 --> 00:39:46.950
And over time, we started
doing really different things.

00:39:46.950 --> 00:39:48.630
I'm not at all trying to compete with Kara

00:39:48.630 --> 00:39:49.740
and all the things she does.

00:39:49.740 --> 00:39:50.700
Again, I think she's doing great.

00:39:50.700 --> 00:39:52.950
I think it's useless to
try to compete with that.

00:39:52.950 --> 00:39:55.020
I'm trying to try to do my own thing.

00:39:55.020 --> 00:39:56.520
That's where you get "Decoder" questions.

00:39:56.520 --> 00:39:57.810
How do I deliver different value?

00:39:57.810 --> 00:39:59.400
How do I make this meaningfully different?

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:02.790
Casey Newton is always saying
the podcast ecosystem is such

00:40:02.790 --> 00:40:05.340
that any person is always
talking to someone else

00:40:05.340 --> 00:40:07.170
and you can find that conversation.

00:40:07.170 --> 00:40:08.490
Like, you can pick two names out of a hat,

00:40:08.490 --> 00:40:09.930
they've done a podcast episode together.

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:11.880
How are you gonna make it different?

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:13.590
So we try to make it different
with "Decoder" questions

00:40:13.590 --> 00:40:15.360
by adding the sort of explainer episodes.

00:40:15.360 --> 00:40:17.850
And we have now gotten to the place

00:40:17.850 --> 00:40:20.580
where I think our own audience data shows,

00:40:20.580 --> 00:40:22.620
people like the episodes where I talk

00:40:22.620 --> 00:40:24.813
more than the episodes
where the CEOs talk,

00:40:26.070 --> 00:40:26.940
that's a victory.

00:40:26.940 --> 00:40:29.310
I feel very weird about
that, but we have it.

00:40:29.310 --> 00:40:31.530
We are hearing the feedback.

00:40:31.530 --> 00:40:32.760
Do the explainer episodes,

00:40:32.760 --> 00:40:34.170
do the DoorDash problem episodes.

00:40:34.170 --> 00:40:36.240
The problem with all that

00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:39.990
is that I am, at my
core, still a reporter,

00:40:39.990 --> 00:40:42.870
and I need to show you my reporting.

00:40:42.870 --> 00:40:44.040
So if I just show up

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:46.800
and do ranted-out video
episodes every week,

00:40:46.800 --> 00:40:49.140
it would be much easier for all of us.

00:40:49.140 --> 00:40:51.600
And as you can tell, I
could probably just do it,

00:40:51.600 --> 00:40:52.890
but if I don't have the reporting,

00:40:52.890 --> 00:40:53.940
I won't feel good about it.

00:40:53.940 --> 00:40:56.700
And so to me a huge part
of the Monday episode

00:40:56.700 --> 00:40:58.650
is just showing my work.

00:40:58.650 --> 00:41:00.540
Here's how I do the things I do.

00:41:00.540 --> 00:41:02.940
Here's where the opinions
I have come from.

00:41:02.940 --> 00:41:06.330
I allow these people to
challenge my opinions

00:41:06.330 --> 00:41:07.920
as directly as they want,

00:41:07.920 --> 00:41:09.270
I challenge theirs.

00:41:09.270 --> 00:41:11.820
I've come to a deeper, more
interesting understanding

00:41:11.820 --> 00:41:13.470
of how this whole industry works,

00:41:13.470 --> 00:41:15.990
of how the masters of the
universe make decisions.

00:41:15.990 --> 00:41:18.420
And then I can show up
on a Thursday episode

00:41:18.420 --> 00:41:20.370
and say, "Hey, I think that sucks"

00:41:20.370 --> 00:41:22.770
and I feel great about
where that came from.

00:41:22.770 --> 00:41:24.330
And there's just some honest dealing

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:25.590
about all that that's important.

00:41:25.590 --> 00:41:27.900
Now, does media training suck?

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:29.190
Are there episodes where,

00:41:29.190 --> 00:41:30.937
in the middle of it, I'm like, "Boy,

00:41:30.937 --> 00:41:32.580
"I could just be talking to AI right now?"

00:41:32.580 --> 00:41:35.850
Yes, I will try to do better
at breaking that down.

00:41:35.850 --> 00:41:37.140
I think one of the big learnings

00:41:37.140 --> 00:41:39.990
we had this year as a team was,

00:41:39.990 --> 00:41:40.980
well, we do a lot of prep.

00:41:40.980 --> 00:41:43.620
Kate and Nick write
amazing prep docs for me.

00:41:43.620 --> 00:41:47.010
And I spend an hour before every
episode just inhaling them.

00:41:47.010 --> 00:41:50.130
And then the more I leave it behind,

00:41:50.130 --> 00:41:51.960
the better off we are, right?

00:41:51.960 --> 00:41:53.580
Where I just let the episodes go

00:41:53.580 --> 00:41:54.840
to wherever I think is interesting

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:57.030
and I don't try to hit all
the questions on the list.

00:41:57.030 --> 00:41:58.310
That's a thing that I'm
gonna start to push on

00:41:58.310 --> 00:42:00.990
to make the interviews more interesting.

00:42:00.990 --> 00:42:02.640
But I do think the core dynamic

00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:05.817
of everybody can see me doing the work

00:42:05.817 --> 00:42:09.150
and that is the foundation
for all the other stuff I say

00:42:09.150 --> 00:42:11.040
that feels very important to me.

00:42:11.040 --> 00:42:12.240
'Cause if I don't show my work,

00:42:12.240 --> 00:42:14.160
I'm not sure how I can earn trust

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:16.440
in a media environment
that looks like this one.

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:17.273
All right, what do you guys think?

00:42:17.273 --> 00:42:18.450
Should we just stop interviewing CEOs?

00:42:18.450 --> 00:42:21.870
- I think you probably won

00:42:21.870 --> 00:42:24.600
or at least came to a
draw versus media training

00:42:24.600 --> 00:42:28.440
for like, like a majority of 2025.

00:42:28.440 --> 00:42:29.640
I can only think of a couple

00:42:29.640 --> 00:42:32.760
that, like, media training really won.

00:42:32.760 --> 00:42:35.190
- I will say that we all know

00:42:35.190 --> 00:42:37.710
when we get someone from
McKinsey on the show

00:42:37.710 --> 00:42:39.213
that it's gonna be a fight.

00:42:40.380 --> 00:42:41.490
Like, if you're a CEO

00:42:41.490 --> 00:42:42.900
and you spent time working at McKinsey,

00:42:42.900 --> 00:42:46.623
like, I come ready for war
against media training.

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:48.653
Like, startup founders,

00:42:48.653 --> 00:42:50.670
we love startup founders
'cause they're all just raw.

00:42:50.670 --> 00:42:51.750
Like, they're just ready to go.

00:42:51.750 --> 00:42:52.920
They will say anything.

00:42:52.920 --> 00:42:54.375
And there's a real dynamic there

00:42:54.375 --> 00:42:55.560
that I think is fascinating.

00:42:55.560 --> 00:42:57.410
But yeah, the consultant class and I,

00:42:59.010 --> 00:43:00.630
it's ex consultants and politicians

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:01.770
where I'm still working on it.

00:43:01.770 --> 00:43:04.140
I've taken to just swearing
at the politicians.

00:43:04.140 --> 00:43:05.310
- You said this before

00:43:05.310 --> 00:43:07.170
where you said that you think some portion

00:43:07.170 --> 00:43:08.640
of the "Decoder" audience just wants you

00:43:08.640 --> 00:43:11.268
to end every episode by arresting a CEO.

00:43:11.268 --> 00:43:12.572
(Nilay laughing)

00:43:12.572 --> 00:43:14.340
I think that's a kind of useful frame too,

00:43:14.340 --> 00:43:16.170
because you know, as much as,

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:17.610
yeah, sometimes you get the McKinsey's,

00:43:17.610 --> 00:43:19.500
you also do, every once in a while,

00:43:19.500 --> 00:43:22.920
get those interviews that
do have explosive moments.

00:43:22.920 --> 00:43:26.430
And then those interviews
I do feel like add fuel

00:43:26.430 --> 00:43:29.640
to the "Decoder" frame for
future interviews, right?

00:43:29.640 --> 00:43:32.250
Because if somebody sees
somebody kind of melt down,

00:43:32.250 --> 00:43:33.457
they come on the show and they go,

00:43:33.457 --> 00:43:34.297
"Oh, well, I can't do that.

00:43:34.297 --> 00:43:37.597
"I don't wanna do what the Intuit CEO did

00:43:37.597 --> 00:43:38.910
"because that's bad."

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:40.380
- I encourage more CEOs to come on

00:43:40.380 --> 00:43:41.520
and do what the Intuit CEO did,

00:43:41.520 --> 00:43:43.080
if you could, that would make my day.

00:43:43.080 --> 00:43:44.100
- I think there is value

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:45.810
in, you know, not treating every interview

00:43:45.810 --> 00:43:47.940
like you're trying to create that moment,

00:43:47.940 --> 00:43:50.340
but like, giving enough room

00:43:50.340 --> 00:43:53.610
where that moment could
happen with almost anybody

00:43:53.610 --> 00:43:56.760
except for maybe the super,
super well media-trained folks,

00:43:56.760 --> 00:43:59.430
does create a good enough dynamic

00:43:59.430 --> 00:44:01.350
that like, you know,

00:44:01.350 --> 00:44:04.500
it's kind of like a
will-it-happen kind of thing.

00:44:04.500 --> 00:44:06.450
- Yeah, look, I read the comments,

00:44:06.450 --> 00:44:07.590
we read all the emails.

00:44:07.590 --> 00:44:09.240
I get the criticism

00:44:09.240 --> 00:44:11.670
that this sometimes
feels like free publicity

00:44:11.670 --> 00:44:15.420
for people who are just trying
to increase the ferocity

00:44:15.420 --> 00:44:17.970
of the capitalist hellhole
in which we all live.

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:21.000
Okay, I think my job as a reporter,

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:24.030
my job as a person who
runs this newsroom is

00:44:24.030 --> 00:44:26.190
to ask the questions as directly as I can.

00:44:26.190 --> 00:44:29.730
And look, I started my career
without any access at all.

00:44:29.730 --> 00:44:33.030
I started as a journalist
making $12 a post

00:44:33.030 --> 00:44:36.720
writing about SD cards for
Engadget, a division of AOL,

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:39.540
like, and that might have
been when I was happiest,

00:44:39.540 --> 00:44:41.820
to be perfectly honest with all of you.

00:44:41.820 --> 00:44:44.430
Like, Nick has actually been
a reporter in our newsroom.

00:44:44.430 --> 00:44:46.500
Like, I'm like, "We should
write about SD cards"

00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:47.333
like all the time. (laughs)

00:44:47.333 --> 00:44:49.380
- Like-
- It's a recurring theme

00:44:49.380 --> 00:44:51.540
since the last 10 years.
- Yeah.

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:54.270
- Being a gadget blogger
might be where my heart is.

00:44:54.270 --> 00:44:55.770
I do not care about the access.

00:44:55.770 --> 00:44:56.603
I really don't.

00:44:56.603 --> 00:44:57.810
I think access is poison.

00:44:57.810 --> 00:45:00.570
I think it it changes your worldview,

00:45:00.570 --> 00:45:02.220
it warps your incentives.

00:45:02.220 --> 00:45:06.570
And my firm belief is that
the less access you need,

00:45:06.570 --> 00:45:07.950
the more you get.

00:45:07.950 --> 00:45:09.000
And that has been borne out

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:10.290
across the entire arc of "The Verge."

00:45:10.290 --> 00:45:12.630
It's been borne out across
the entire arc of "Decoder."

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:14.460
We are at the point, I keep saying this,

00:45:14.460 --> 00:45:16.470
the audience is like, "We
just want you to talk."

00:45:16.470 --> 00:45:18.480
That is a very powerful position to be in.

00:45:18.480 --> 00:45:19.920
So we're gonna keep earning that,

00:45:19.920 --> 00:45:22.170
but then I should use
that to get the access

00:45:22.170 --> 00:45:23.790
that other people have to, like, ask for

00:45:23.790 --> 00:45:25.800
or make concessions to get.

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:26.667
And we don't have to do that

00:45:26.667 --> 00:45:28.230
and I won't ever do that.

00:45:28.230 --> 00:45:29.910
And I think that puts me in a position

00:45:29.910 --> 00:45:32.460
where we can create more of
these moments of conflict,

00:45:32.460 --> 00:45:35.010
more adversarial moments of journalism,

00:45:35.010 --> 00:45:37.560
but we also have to not be rude.

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:40.170
Like, the people have to
want to show up and engage

00:45:40.170 --> 00:45:42.060
and be honest with me.

00:45:42.060 --> 00:45:44.460
And so I think sometimes people see,

00:45:44.460 --> 00:45:46.890
like, decorum as concession

00:45:46.890 --> 00:45:49.500
and there's nothing I can do about that.

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:51.840
They have to open their web browser

00:45:51.840 --> 00:45:54.120
and look into a camera and talk to me.

00:45:54.120 --> 00:45:55.400
And the fact that often they're not even

00:45:55.400 --> 00:45:58.740
in the same room as me
means leaving is trivial.

00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:00.510
It's like, you're a Command + W away

00:46:00.510 --> 00:46:01.530
from ending this interaction.

00:46:01.530 --> 00:46:04.470
And so you do have to walk
the line a little bit.

00:46:04.470 --> 00:46:06.600
- This actually brings us very well

00:46:06.600 --> 00:46:09.060
to the last question we have for you.

00:46:09.060 --> 00:46:12.720
Listener Jeremy Curl
wrote in with frustration

00:46:12.720 --> 00:46:15.900
with tech journalism podcasts overall.

00:46:15.900 --> 00:46:19.957
And he writes, "The tech
industry is creating

00:46:19.957 --> 00:46:21.847
"and exacerbating problems within society.

00:46:21.847 --> 00:46:23.287
"Aren't we way past the point

00:46:23.287 --> 00:46:25.267
"of looking at tech as cool and fun

00:46:25.267 --> 00:46:27.937
"and definitively going
to solve all problems.

00:46:27.937 --> 00:46:30.637
"There is some deep, dark
shit happening because of tech

00:46:30.637 --> 00:46:34.080
"and it has the power to
really tear apart society."

00:46:34.080 --> 00:46:35.250
That's a very valid point.

00:46:35.250 --> 00:46:36.817
He adds, "We need tech journalism

00:46:36.817 --> 00:46:39.277
"to be better at shining a
light on these troubling issues,

00:46:39.277 --> 00:46:41.797
"otherwise, a podcast sounds
like two people hanging out

00:46:41.797 --> 00:46:43.140
"at a dinner party."

00:46:43.140 --> 00:46:45.060
So based on that, what does the future

00:46:45.060 --> 00:46:48.261
of "Decoder" in 2026 look like to you?

00:46:48.261 --> 00:46:50.100
(both laughing)

00:46:50.100 --> 00:46:52.830
- Yeah, I don't disagree at all.

00:46:52.830 --> 00:46:53.663
Not one bit.

00:46:53.663 --> 00:46:56.910
I think the "Decoder"
team shares that worldview

00:46:56.910 --> 00:46:57.877
in a very real way.

00:46:57.877 --> 00:47:00.330
"The Verge" is built on that worldview.

00:47:00.330 --> 00:47:02.010
When we started in 2011,

00:47:02.010 --> 00:47:04.710
the idea that technology
would just change culture

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:06.990
was not taken for granted.

00:47:06.990 --> 00:47:09.150
Like, this was our pitch.

00:47:09.150 --> 00:47:10.080
Like, we're starting a new website.

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:11.871
It's about technology and
culture being the same thing.

00:47:11.871 --> 00:47:13.522
And everyone was like,
"What are you talking about?

00:47:13.522 --> 00:47:14.355
"It's cell phones, right?

00:47:14.355 --> 00:47:15.900
"You're doing cell phones."

00:47:15.900 --> 00:47:18.630
It turns out cell phones have
changed the entire world.

00:47:18.630 --> 00:47:19.800
Like, we were correct.

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:20.940
We bet correctly,

00:47:20.940 --> 00:47:22.170
but it was not obvious when we started,

00:47:22.170 --> 00:47:23.490
the way it is obvious now.

00:47:23.490 --> 00:47:25.140
That's still our foundation,
that's still our thesis.

00:47:25.140 --> 00:47:26.430
We do a lot of that coverage.

00:47:26.430 --> 00:47:29.100
That's where a bunch of angry emails

00:47:29.100 --> 00:47:30.600
about covering Trump came from.

00:47:30.600 --> 00:47:32.460
Were committed to that coverage.

00:47:32.460 --> 00:47:33.840
You know, my thesis of the early part

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:35.550
of the Trump administration and DOGE

00:47:35.550 --> 00:47:38.040
was a bunch of tech bros

00:47:38.040 --> 00:47:40.230
realized the government runs on databases

00:47:40.230 --> 00:47:43.200
and they could just take over
the databases and delete them

00:47:43.200 --> 00:47:44.880
and that would change the government.

00:47:44.880 --> 00:47:46.203
And it kind of worked.

00:47:47.670 --> 00:47:48.503
That's weird.

00:47:48.503 --> 00:47:49.950
That's just a weird outcome that happened

00:47:49.950 --> 00:47:52.500
along the way of the Trump administration

00:47:52.500 --> 00:47:55.590
being a political force
that started on cell phones.

00:47:55.590 --> 00:47:58.140
So there's some combination there.

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:00.390
The thing I will caution you about,

00:48:00.390 --> 00:48:02.220
and I'll caution everybody about is

00:48:02.220 --> 00:48:04.800
if you make your focus relentlessly that,

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:06.540
you will only attract an audience

00:48:06.540 --> 00:48:08.040
of people who care about that.

00:48:08.880 --> 00:48:12.540
You will narrow the amount
of impact that you can have.

00:48:12.540 --> 00:48:14.400
And so we have a big audience of people

00:48:14.400 --> 00:48:16.140
who do like technology,

00:48:16.140 --> 00:48:18.600
who do think it should
be used for good things.

00:48:18.600 --> 00:48:21.840
Who are excited about
the craziest Wi-Fi router

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:23.640
on display at CES.

00:48:23.640 --> 00:48:25.530
I'm one of those people.

00:48:25.530 --> 00:48:27.090
We should do a lot of "Decoder" episodes

00:48:27.090 --> 00:48:28.890
about the Raspberry Pi
that runs my smart home.

00:48:28.890 --> 00:48:31.080
Like, I would love to do that.

00:48:31.080 --> 00:48:33.630
I think the trick is taking that audience

00:48:33.630 --> 00:48:35.160
that sees the benefit of technology,

00:48:35.160 --> 00:48:36.720
who loves it for its own sake,

00:48:36.720 --> 00:48:39.090
and saying these are the consequences.

00:48:39.090 --> 00:48:40.830
These are the implications

00:48:40.830 --> 00:48:42.720
of the choices that are
being made by the companies

00:48:42.720 --> 00:48:44.670
that are developing the
technologies that you love.

00:48:44.670 --> 00:48:46.260
And there's a lot there.

00:48:46.260 --> 00:48:48.120
I'll give a really dumb example.

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:50.220
And this is the very small thing

00:48:50.220 --> 00:48:52.140
that was a genesis of all
of our policy coverage

00:48:52.140 --> 00:48:52.973
here at "The Verge."

00:48:52.973 --> 00:48:55.620
Do you remember the, like, iPhone 3GS

00:48:55.620 --> 00:48:57.150
and the iPhone 4 had bad service,

00:48:57.150 --> 00:48:58.230
like, they dropped a lot of calls.

00:48:58.230 --> 00:48:59.063
- Yeah.

00:48:59.063 --> 00:49:00.930
- So we're like, we were
running Engadget at the time,

00:49:00.930 --> 00:49:03.330
and you're like, well, how
does the iPhone drop calls?

00:49:03.330 --> 00:49:04.163
There's an Antennagate.

00:49:04.163 --> 00:49:06.840
And you start with the iPhone drops calls

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:08.040
and you're like, it's
not really the iPhone,

00:49:08.040 --> 00:49:08.873
it's AT&amp;T.

00:49:08.873 --> 00:49:10.140
Why does AT&amp;T drop calls?

00:49:10.140 --> 00:49:11.760
It's 'cause our 3G network is overloaded.

00:49:11.760 --> 00:49:13.050
It's 'cause they don't
have enough spectrum.

00:49:13.050 --> 00:49:14.100
And the government is actually

00:49:14.100 --> 00:49:16.560
gonna shut down the analog TV system

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:20.280
to re-farm 700-megahertz spectrum for LTE

00:49:20.280 --> 00:49:21.177
and that will solve the iPhone.

00:49:21.177 --> 00:49:24.120
And you end up at, now we cover the FCC.

00:49:24.120 --> 00:49:25.200
Like, very quickly,

00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:28.518
you end up at here's
how FCC auctions work.

00:49:28.518 --> 00:49:29.730
And that to me,

00:49:29.730 --> 00:49:31.590
that's the link I wanna make to people.

00:49:31.590 --> 00:49:33.870
Here's this experience
you're having on your phone

00:49:33.870 --> 00:49:36.780
and here's this entire structure

00:49:36.780 --> 00:49:38.100
that explains that experience.

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:39.810
That's why the show is called "Decoder."

00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:41.670
And a lot of that structure
looks like capitalism.

00:49:41.670 --> 00:49:42.690
A lot of that structure looks like

00:49:42.690 --> 00:49:44.070
here's how org charts work.

00:49:44.070 --> 00:49:46.920
But even more of that structure is

00:49:46.920 --> 00:49:48.780
here's how it makes you feel

00:49:48.780 --> 00:49:51.180
and, like, here's how people
are managing those feelings

00:49:51.180 --> 00:49:52.110
about the experience.

00:49:52.110 --> 00:49:53.220
You feel bad about DoorDash,

00:49:53.220 --> 00:49:55.050
you're still using DoorDash.

00:49:55.050 --> 00:49:56.460
That's The Verge," that's "Decoder."

00:49:56.460 --> 00:49:57.760
We're gonna keep doing it.

00:49:58.950 --> 00:50:01.020
Again, the caution is you don't
wanna narrow your audience

00:50:01.020 --> 00:50:02.820
to people who wanna feel bad.

00:50:02.820 --> 00:50:05.280
You want to expand your audience
to people who love things

00:50:05.280 --> 00:50:09.337
and say, "Actually your
interest, your enthusiasm,

00:50:09.337 --> 00:50:11.812
"that can be the push to make
some of this stuff better."

